{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb27e3af-03c6-4622-97e8-edffbb4dc235","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` | `[Fact(Skip = \"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Ignore(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Skip(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n\n**Notes:**\n- For xUnit `[Theory]` tests, use `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`.\n- MSTest and NUnit both use `[Ignore]` but they're from different namespaces (`Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting` vs `NUnit.Framework`).\n- All four frameworks require a reason string.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3cea185c-4ec1-4556-bd1a-c9e693314b2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for each of the four .NET test frameworks: MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. Let me provide a concise answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"340A:183D91:C544D4:E4BEB6:69F3FF13"},"id":"f05f87f1-6178-4e7e-be38-d39ef111ab5b","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:17:13.405Z","parentId":"9c347e4d-bef5-4ead-acd8-e121453658f5"}
